  "name": "Modern Dance: Breaking Ground",
  "description": "Modern dance begins with a refusal — Isadora Duncan takes off her shoes and corset. What follows is 120 years of artists inventing new ways to move, each generation rebelling against the last while building on it. This grammar maps the pioneers (Duncan, Graham, Cunningham), the lineage chains that connect them, and the meta-movements (liberation, system-building, system-demolishing, synthesis) that give the story its shape.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Photographs of Isadora Duncan by Arnold Genthe (1910s-1920s). Edward Steichen photographs of Martha Graham. Bauhaus stage design sketches by Oskar Schlemmer. Ruth St. Denis photographs in orientalist costume (early 1900s).",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "tags": ["dance", "modern", "contemporary", "embodiment", "innovation", "rebellion", "lineage"],
  "roots": ["embodiment", "liberation", "western-philosophy"],
  "shelves": ["wonder", "resilience"],
  "lineages": ["Akomolafe", "Andreotti"],
  "worldview": "dialectical",
